Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
createPinBlkg(25.10)                                      createPinBlkg(25.10)

Name
       createPinBlkg - Creates a pin blockage for a module

Syntax
       createPinBlkg

       [-help] [-cell  <cell_name>] [-layer {<layer_id_list>}]

       {  -area  <{x1  y1 x2 y2>} | [-edge <edge_number> [[-offset_start <dis-
       tance>] [-offset_end <distance>]]] |

       [-abutted_master_clone_channel_access_only     [-feedthru_blockage_file
       <file_name>]] }

       [ -name <blockage_name> [ -includePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>}
       | -excludePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>} ]]

       Creates  a  pin  blockage for a module. You can run this command on the
       top-level module also. You can use this command during partition floor-
       planning.

Parameters
       -abutted_master_clone_channel_access_only
              Creates pin blockages on abutted  edges  of  master-clones  that
              abut to its parent or other master-clones.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -area <x1 y1 x2 y2>
              Specifies  the lower left x coordinate, lower left y coordinate,
              upper right x coordinate, and upper right y  coordinate  respec-
              tively of the blockage area.

              Note:  The values of x1, y1, x2, and y2 are relative to the top-
              level coordinates.

              Data_type: box, optional

       -cell <cell_name>
              Specifies the module for which the pin blockage will be created.

              * If -cell option is not used, then the blockage applies to top-
                level pins only.

              * If -cell option is used,  then  only,  the  Partition/Blackbox
                pins will be considered.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -edge <edge_number>
              Specifies  the  integer  value  where edge numbering starts from
              lower-left corner of a partition clock-wise. Edge 0 is the  edge
              that has the smallest y value.

              Data_type: int, optional

       -excludePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>}
              Specifies the pin-list on which the pin-blockage is not applica-
              ble. Pins which are specified in this list can be placed in this
              area legally.

              Note:  The  -excludePinPatterns  and -includePinPatterns options
              are mutually exclusive and cannot be used in a  single  command.
              Both  these options require the use of the -name option to spec-
              ify the name of the partition pin blockage.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -feedthru_blockage_file <file_name>
              Outputs a file with coordinates of blocked edges for pin assign-
              ment transformed into feedthru blockage_file format.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each createPinBlkg parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man createPinBlkg

       -includePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>}
              Specifies  the pin-list on which the pin-blockage is applicable.
              All other pins can be placed in this area legally.

              Note: The -excludePinPatterns  and  -includePinPatterns  options
              are  mutually  exclusive and cannot be used in a single command.
              Both these options require the use of the -name option to  spec-
              ify the name of the partition pin blockage.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -layer {<layer_id_list>}
              Specifies  the  metal layer(s) for which pins are not to be cre-
              ated.

              Note: Layers can be specified using the LEF layer names or layer
              ID numbers.

              Default: If no layer number is specified, all metal  layers  are
              blocked.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -name <blockage_name>
              Specifies the name of the partition pin blockage.

              Default: By default, the name is defPtnPinBlkName.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -offset_end <distance>
              Specifies  the  distance,  in microns, from the ending corner of
              the edge.

              Minimum  Value: 0

              Maximum Value: 65535

              Data_type: float, optional

       -offset_start <distance>
              Specifies the distance, in microns, from the starting corner  of
              the edge.

              Minimum  Value: 0

              Maximum Value: 65535

              Data_type: float, optional

Examples
              * The following command creates a pin blockage named pinBlkg1 on
                the  edge  0  of  layers  Metal5  and  Metal7  for  the module
                PtnBlock1.

                createPinBlkg -edge 0 -name pinBlkg1  -cell  PtnBlock1  -layer
                {Metal5 Metal7}

              * The following command creates a pin blockage named pinBlkg2 on
                layers  Metal5 and Metal7 for the module PtnBlock2. The block-
                age area is bounded by the lower-left coordinates 100, 200 and
                the upper-right coordinates 300, 400.

                createPinBlkg -area 100  200  300  400  -name  pinBlkg2  -cell
                PtnBlock2 -layer {Metal5 Metal7}

              *

                The  following  command  creates a pin blockage named pinBlkg3
                that only applies to partition pins that  match  pattern1  and
                pattern2.  All other partition pins can be placed in this area
                legally.

                createPinBlkg  -includePinPatterns   {*pattern1*   *pattern2*}
                -cell PtnBlock3 -area $area -name pinBlkg3

              * The  following  command  creates a pin blockage named pinBlkg4
                that only applies to all  partition  pins  except  those  that
                match pattern1 and pattern2. Only pins that match pattern1 and
                pattern2 can be placed at this edge legally.

                createPinBlkg   -excludePinPatterns   {*pattern1*  *pattern2*}
                -cell PtnBlock4 -edge 0 -name pinBlkg4

